<br>
&quot;I'll kill all of you- I'll kill all of yooouu!!&quot; he growled.  An old-fashioned sword lay on the mattress, a black-bladed scimitar with a wooden hilt.  The cheap leather scabbard had been burned already, just like the essence of his soul.  The being that was once Derek was now totally consumed; burned away, ravaged, destroyed by the savage beast known only to those who've never loved it, never lived it, as fire.<br>
<br>
Gasoline dripped from scalded fingers.  No hair existed on his shaken hands, quaking at the mere presence of an unlit match in his extremeties.  There was never any water to put out the fires- save the saline tears that he excreted.  There were two gallon-sized buckets in the corner, nearly full of the stuff. Another 5-gallon oil jug sat next to them, the clear plastic tainted with crimson liquid.  Blowtorches and barrels, their combustible contents previously drained, rolled around outside the little room in the middle of nowhere.  Scars traced up and down his arms, all in unison, all in rows.  They reminded him of badges of rank, some kind of ritual.  Ritual... oh yeah...<br>
<br>
Derek, or who used to be Derek, powered his near lifeless hands towards the chrome bowl.  Therein sat a trio of pictures; a man in a Hawaiian shirt and khaki shorts surrounded by colleagues, and the importance of the other two escaped him.  All he remembered is that he had drawn sigils and runes on the back with lines of StiXy-suLfur brand combustable gel-powder.  He traced the lines along with the quite large black sword on the side of the bed, weak arms quivering with the effort.  His arms had shrank fully two sizes, his pants literally falling off of him.  But what did food matter anymore?  They were all dead.<br>
<br>
And now Them would all pay.  Oh yes.  Them.<br>
<br>
Not recalling exactly who &quot;Them&quot; referred to, Derek's stomach lurched just before he had properly folded the color picture so that the fire would burn it up best, completely and fully, without a piece of ash remaining.  Just how he would burn Them.  Them would burn, if not by him then by someone else, but they'd BURN!<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, his mind went off before he was able to finish folding.  Fires burned behind his eyes, and he saw the visions again.  The icy waters; Brooklyn.  The weights tied to Jash's legs, and the cold, icy waters.  Mika, tied to a chair, bludgeoned repeatedly.  Devin, a shower, and electrodes.  Jerron... well, a plain ass bullet- the tasers and injections had little effect.  Carmen and the skyrise.  Worst of all... Nefertiti.  He didn't even try to rationalize it; he felt the bodies, he smelled the blood.  He even tasted Nefer's lips as they plunged the dagger into her back when they embraced for the last time.<br>
<br>
He roared in blissful rage, the unleashing of emotions erasing all memories for the present.  There was no pain, no family-wide death; just the blood dripping from his mouth, and the sudden combustion of the paper in his hands.  Torrents ripped through his head, wracking his body, tumbling Derek off the bed, and forcing him to wretch the lack of contents in his stomach.  Bile welled up in his throat... and even the floorboards caught fire.<br>
<br>
He realized he was still holdind the burning picture of his enemy; it was black char.  His friends- no,  family!!  They were still on the bed!  And it was burning quickly...<br>
<br>
Summoning the last ounce of strength he posessed, Derek willed himself to the corner, to his saved saline fire solution, and doused the burning bed.  His fingers traced slowly over the captured images of his best friends, the only family he'd ever known.  More pain burned inside at the reminder of their loss, but this image pushed their deaths away for one last moment.  His hand lingered over the picture, secure in its frame, before he picked it up.  Seared flesh touched grainy wood; and six souls seemed to touch one.  Again, Derek fell to the floor, and again, and explosion rocked his previous home.  He could almost smell Nefertiti, could almost feel her presence, as he always used to.  DAMN! his mind finally cried out.  The entire room had gone up in a blaze; another gas can had spille over, and he watched the heat shimmer into plasma above the spilled puddle, working its way towards the source of gasoline.<br>
<br>
No...  This wrecked orphanage was all he had left; it would NOT go down in flames, the way his life had, the way his friends had, the way his love had!!  In a last desparate attempt, he dove for the half-full jug of blood, and succesfully diluted the stream enough to stop the rush of flame...<br>
<br>
But it was still too late.  The flames had spread from the room, and into the neighboring rooms.  Chaz's Pad, they called it, directly across from his own, was where he stored the lion's share of the combustibles, just like the drugs back in the day.  There was no more house anymore; just a flash of light, and memories.  &quot;Titi...&quot;  Sidewalk, bright sun.  Scecnt bubblegum shampoo? Flash- burning stairs, walk lightly.  &quot;I love you.&quot;  &quot;Heehee!  I love you too,  Der-Der!&quot; Doorway.  Falling rafter; DIVE!! &quot;No, Titi, that's not what I-&quot; Stone walkway; safe.  On your feet!  Now tell her.  Before you go for good!  &quot;Ahh, who cares?-&quot; YOU FOOL! &quot;-Wanna get ice cream?&quot;  No...  &quot;Yay~~!  Can we go to Mr. Smirgles?&quot;  nononono...  &quot;Sure, why not?&quot;  Did I... did I ever tell her-<br>
<br>
&quot;Nef... Neffy?&quot; He could have sworn he saw her, if a bit thin, standing in front of him- before he staggered to kiss the rock.<br>
<br>
